<TEXT>
executions are down this year even in 
the nations capital punishment capital as courts finetune 
the laws and deathrow inmates wait to see what effect that will 
have on their cases 
in texas this year only robert streetman has been belted to the 
gurney and executed by injection while eight convicts have been 
put to death nationally last year texas accounted for six of the 
25 us executions and 10 of 18 in 1986 
since the us supreme court ruled the death penalty legal in 
1976 101 inmates have been put to death 27 of them in the lone 
star state 
its kind of like everybody is saying ok lets wait a 
minute said james beathard an inmate on the texas death row 
texas has a great deal to do with it tanya coke research 
director for the naacp legal defense fund said of the lull the 
courts heard major death penalty cases which challenge the 
constitutionality of the texas law and essentially held them up 
this summer however the us supreme court upheld the death 
sentence of donald gene franklin for the 1975 murder of a nurse 
and assistant attorney general bob walt said franklin and others 
will run out of time later this year 
i think youre probably going to see three or four by the end 
of the year walt said franklin is an absolute certainty 
nationwide in the last year many court opinions in death 
penalty cases went against the states walt said 
there seems to be a little bit of finetuning in state 
statutes he said 
in the franklin case defense attorneys argued that the jury 
that voted for the death penalty was prevented from giving full 
consideration to mitigating circumstances or factors suggesting 
life in prison as more appropriate 
during the trial franklins attorneys had suggested the judge 
instruct the jury on how to handle mitigating circumstances but he 
refused 
death penalty opponents now are pinning their hopes on a new 
texas case the us supreme court has agreed to hear attorneys for 
johnny penry contend he should not be executed for a 1979 murder 
because he is mentally retarded 
arguments in the penry case wont be delivered until later this 
year with no immediate ruling likely 
franklin although portrayed as a bad decision was a good 
case said scott howe an attorney with the capital punishment 
clinic at the university of texas law school people got a stay 
on the franklin issue were hoping most people get a stay on penry 
now 
the ruling in the franklin case came eight months after he was 
scheduled to be executed 
on death row inmates are just pleased the issue remains active 
were back eight months now when we were talking about 
franklin said inmate lester bower now were talking about 
penry and we have not even had a test case on it yet 
of execution dates pending in texas walter bells on sept 13 
is considered the most serious bell was convicted of the 1974 
slaying of a port arthur couple 
hes on his second time through the appeals process walt 
said historically he has a greater chance of being executed 
but howe said questions raised in bells appeal are very good 
since they are similar to penrys hes mentally retarded he 
said theres a question if applied to bell whether the texas 
statute is constitutional 
those involved in capital punishment matters agree that 
electionyear politics is really not a factor 
republicans generally prodeath penalty are eager to make it 
a difficult issue on democrats generally antideath penalty 
ms coke said but in terms of real impact on cases no 
death penalty law is complex and constantly evolving and as 
soon as a court hands down a new procedure it seems a new case 
comes along that breaks the mold i think the courts struggles 
with capital punishment attest to human frailty its simply 
impossible to reduce to a legal formula decisions of life and 
death 
