<TEXT>
the growth of government power to tax and 
regulate may be in its twilight years as modern technology 
makes it easier for businesses to move from place to place 
according to a private study 
richard b mckenzie an economics professor at clemson 
university in south carolina said computers facsimile machines 
satellites and other technologies have enabled businesses to 
respond to government intrusion by going elsewhere 
mckenzie conducted his study for the washingtonbased cato 
institute a policy analysis and research organization which 
generally follows a libertarian philosophy of encouraging the least 
possible government intervention in human affairs 
capital is being freed from the strict confines of arbitrary 
national boundaries he wrote as a consequence the power of 
government to tax and regulate may be in its twilight years 
the study said that in the past manufacturers historically 
concentrated their operations in fixed industrial centers the 
costs of relocating factories was high so governments could impose 
taxes and regulations without worrying about capital flight 
as a result governments grew steadily larger and more complex 
he said 
all that has changed as electronic technology tied the world 
more closely together economically and geographic boundaries were 
erased mckenzie said 
the computer that once filled a room can now sit on someones 
lap the textile loom once the size of a car is no larger than a 
birdbath company records have been transferred from large file 
cabinets onto tiny electronic chips 
mckenzie said the difficulty and cost of longdistance 
communications in the past forced businesses to stay close to one 
another 
today it is cheap and easy for a business executive to call up 
on a computer screen the competitive bids for a job that can be 
performed as easily in st louis as in camden sc or 
trincomalee sri lanka 
mckenzie said managers can effortlessly shift plans and designs 
from place to place and transfer financial capital from one country 
to another at the press of a computer button 
in doing do modern managers can escape the reckless authority 
of government to regulate and control he wrote and in doing 
so they force legislators to think carefully about the economic as 
well as the political constraints on their governing roles 
mckenzie said that while government is not getting smaller in 
absolute terms there is evidence of a slowdown in growth of 
government he said us government spending has grown more slowly 
than the gross national product in recent years 
similar trends are occurring in japan west germany britain and 
china he said 
government competition to stabilize or lower tax rates extends 
beyond these industrial giants to many smaller countries including 
singapore south korea the philippines indonesia turkey 
jamaica colombia bolivia mexico grenada botswana ciskei 
mauritius india and israel 
mckenzie said governments can be expected to react to their 
diminishing power with rhetorical bashing of competitors like 
japan and south korea and efforts to conceal the costs of new 
programs by such tactics as shifting to businesses the 
responsibility for such programs as child care and health insurance 
nonetheless mckenzie concludes that the world will likely be 
beset with an enormous power of government to tax and regulate for 
as long as can be imagined 
</TEXT>
