<TEXT>
breaking up may be hard to do but its a great 
way to get the attention of the people who matter most bruce 
bickner might say 
bickner is neither a lonely hearts columnist nor a pop 
psychologist offering advice to the lovelorn he is president of 
dekalb corp an illinois conglomerate that is about to break up 
into three possibly four publicly traded companies 
the scheduled aug 31 split will allow each of dekalbs lines of 
business oil and gas exploration agricultural genetics oilwell 
servicing and irrigationequipment manufacturing to stand alone 
investors have been gobbling up dekalbs stock in anticipation 
of the restructuring in the 10 months since the company announced 
the plan its stock price has soared from about 20 to near 32 
but behind the rising value of dekalbs stock are the buy 
recommendations of research analysts who largely had ignored the 
company until its breakup plans became apparent 
dekalb had net income of 429 million on revenues of 367 
million last year compared with a 1986 loss of 507 million on 
revenues of 4067 million but despite the companys greatly 
improved performance since 1986 dekalb found few analysts willing 
to follow a firm with such disparate interests 
the large investment houses just dont seem to cooperate 
across industry lines bickner said in a recent interview in 
chicago dekalb is based in the northern illinois city of dekalb 
somebody who covers the food industry and would by nature 
understand dekalbs agricultural business would be reluctant to 
cover dekalb because they dont know what to do with the oil 
business he said if theyre writing a report on dekalb and 
most of dekalbs assets are in oil and gas reserves what are they 
going to say about the stock 
several analysts now following the company agreed that dekalbs 
diversification regarded as a plus in the 1960s and 1970s worked 
against its stock value in the past two years even though the 
